      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and kept seeing stuff about lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles and how the body gets rid of it after a set? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! When you do a high-intensity interval training (HIIT) workout, your muscles are like a bustling city of hardworking citizens, and lactic acid is the pesky little goblin that shows up when the workload gets too heavy. As you push your muscles to their limits, they start to produce energy through a process called anaerobic glycolysis. This process generates lactic acid as a byproduct, much like a goblin might leave behind a trail of trouble when he's too busy causing chaos.\n\nNow, when the lactic acid goblin shows up, your body has a few ways to deal with it. One way is to shuttle it away from the muscles and into the bloodstream, where it can be transported to the liver. In the liver, the lactic acid goblin gets converted back into glucose, which can be used as energy again. This process is called the Cori cycle, and it's like a magical portal that helps your body clear out the lactic acid goblin and keep the city running smoothly.\n\nBut sometimes, the lactic acid goblin can cause a bit of a ruckus, leading to that familiar burning sensation in your muscles. This is your body's way of telling you that the lactic acid gob",
